INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Slime","In one of the bowls, mix ¼ cup of water and ¼ cup of white school glue. If you would like colored slime, add a few drops of food coloring to the solution.","0");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Slime","","1");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Slime","In another bowl, mix ½ tbs Borax with ½ a cup of water and stir until the borax has dissolved.","2");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Slime","","3");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Slime","Add the borax solution to the glue solution and mix. You can also pour the solutions into a re-sealable plastic bag and mix.","4");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Slime","","5");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Slime","A slime-like texture should begin to form immediately. Continue to stir and knead until you get the consistency you want.","6");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Slime","","7");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Slime","Remove your slime from the bowl (or bag) and enjoy.","8");
INSERT INTO Arts (Name, Img) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","0");
INSERT INTO Material(Name,Material) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","A wide bottle (or a fancy drinking glass or wide glass vase), food coloring, vegetable oil, water, and an Alka-seltzer tablet.");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","Step 1: The Oil","0");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","","1");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","Fill the container about 3/4 with vegetable oil. You can choose the size of the container based on how much vegetable oil you have to spare.","2");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","","3");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","Step 2: The Water","4");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","","5");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","Fill the rest of the container with water, leaving 2-3 inches at the top. Watch the water fall through the vegetable oil and settle at the bottom. Can you believe that water is more dense than oil? Water molecules are \"polar\" and oil molecules are \"non-polar\", so they are not attracted to each other in the least. ","6");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","","7");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","Step 3: The Color","8");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","","9");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","What color would you like the \"lava\" in your lava lamp to be? After the water has settled for a minute or so, add you food coloring. We added about 10 drops. Watch as each drop falls through the oil and sits on top of the water layer. Wait until all of the water droplets break through the oil/water line and burst into the water. ","10");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","","11");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","Step 4: The Bubbles","12");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","","13");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Lava Lamp","Drop your Alka-seltzer tablet in and let the games begin! The Alka-seltzer water reaction produces carbon dioxide gas bubbles which stick to the water droplets. The water/gas combo is less dense than the vegetable oil, so they rise to the top. The gas bubbles then break and are released into the air and the water sinks back down to the bottom to start over again! ","14");
INSERT INTO Arts (Name, Img) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","0");
INSERT INTO Material(Name,Material) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","  1 inch (2.5 cm) wide PVC Pipe about 24 inches (60cm) long. You can also use a regular balloon if you do not have PVC pipe.");
INSERT INTO Material(Name,Material) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","  Mylar tinsel for Christmas trees. There are many types of tinsel and many will not work – you should look for the thinnest and narrowest possible. ");
INSERT INTO Material(Name,Material) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","  A head of clean, dry hair");
INSERT INTO Material(Name,Material) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","  Scissors");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","","0");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","  Arrange 6 strands of mylar together and tie them together in a knot at one end.","1");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","  Tie them together again about 6 inches (15cm) from the first knot.","2");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","  Cut the loose mylar strands off just past each knot.","3");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","  Charge the PVC pipe by rubbing it back and forth through your hair for 10 seconds.","4");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","  Hold the mylar orb (by the knot) above the charged pipe and let it drop and touch the pipe.","5");
INSERT INTO Instruction(Name,Instruction,StepNumber) VALUES ("Levitating Orb","  It should repel away and start floating. If the tinsel keeps sticking to the pipe, the tinsel is probably not thin enough and you will need to try another kind of tinsel or order some from us. (You will usually have to “recharge” the pipe before each levitation.)","6");
